<Overview>
    <FormattedContent><![CDATA[

<h1>Welcome to the qualification task for food image segmentation!</h1>

This is a research project of the <a href="https://www.digitalepidemiologylab.org" target="_blank">Digital Epidemiology Lab</a> of the Swiss Federal Institute of Technology in Lausanne/Geneva!
We are training computer vision models to identify different foods, and <b>we need your help to get good training data!</b>
Please read these instructions carefully and take a short quiz before starting to help us with our HITs!

<h2>Instructions for the task</h2>
<ul>
    <li>In the task, you will use the tracing tool to draw a shape around each food item that appears in the image.</li>
    <li>By food item, we mean recognizable foods or dishes like <b>apple pie</b>, <b>pizza</b>, <b>carrot</b>, <b>salad</b>, etc.</li>
    <li>We may provide an example of a food item that we think is present in the image.</li>
    <li>If you're not sure what this example item is, please use the search tool to look at example images.</li>
    <li>If there are no food items of any kind in the image, click the <b>No food item(s) in this image</b> button to flag it.</li>
    <li>
        <b>You should usually trace each item separately</b>,
        but if you see more than 10 instances of the <b>same</b> food clustered together (for example a bunch of grapes)
        then trace around that entire region.
    </li>
    <li><b>Please do not include tableware (bowls, plates, forks, etc.).</b></li>
    <li>Your shapes should closely follow the object boundaries, so use the <b>Zoom</b> button if needed!</li>
</ul>

<h2>What to expect from us</h2>
<ul>
    <li>The vast majority of workers have done a great job on our task so far.</li>
    <li>Expect to spend an average of around 45 seconds per task, but remember that some images will require much more time than others.</li>
    <li>We have unfortunately had to reject assignments by workers who submitted careless work.</li>
    <li>Please contact us if something is unclear!</li>
</ul>

<h2>Good examples</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        This segmentation is good because the grapes should be considered as one contiguous region.
        <img alt="grapes" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/bunch_of_grapes.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This segmentation is good because each cookie is traced separately.
        <img alt="cookies" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/cookies_separate.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This user traced carefully around each of the two sandwiches as two <b>separate</b> shapes.
        <img alt="good: separation of instances" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/trace_instances_separately_good_example.png" height="200" />
    </li>
</ul>


<h2>Bad examples that have been rejected</h2>
<ul>
    <li>
        This user did not verify that the bottom of the image was visible.
        Make sure your window is big enough to see the full image!
        <img alt="missed bottom of image" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/screen_too_small.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This user did not trace the two sandwiches separately.
        <img alt="bad: grouping of two instances" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/trace_instances_separately_bad_example.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This user did not closely follow the object boundary.
        <img alt="sloppy tracing" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/sloppy_tracing.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This user traced the burger but did not create a second shape for the fries.
        <img alt="missing instance" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/missing_instance.png" height="200" />
    </li>
    <li>
        This image needs to be segmented into several pieces - one segment per piece of meat, one for the lemon,
        and one for each piece of potato. <b>When in doubt, create separate shapes!</b>
        <img alt="needs separate segments for each food item" src="https://s3.eu-central-1.amazonaws.com/myfoodrepo-bing-images/static_qualification/includes_extraneous_foods_and_not_split.png" height="200" />
    </li>
</ul>

<h2>Please complete this short multiple-choice quiz to qualify for our food tracing tasks!</h2>

